WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:27.382 align:middle line:84%
[Silence ] [Music ]
>> Regina Meredith:

00:00:27.382 --> 00:00:30.959 align:middle line:84%
It's been a few months since we
spoke with Andy Hoffman last,

00:00:30.959 --> 00:00:33.234 align:middle line:84%
and much has changed
within the economy.

00:00:33.234 --> 00:00:35.723 align:middle line:84%
For one, we had a federal
government shutdown which

00:00:35.723 --> 00:00:37.271 align:middle line:90%
we're still reverberating from.

00:00:37.271 --> 00:00:39.240 align:middle line:90%
Next, we have Obamacare.

00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:42.309 align:middle line:84%
No one knows the toll this is
going to take on our economy.

00:00:42.309 --> 00:00:44.017 align:middle line:84%
In addition, rumors
have been heightening

00:00:44.017 --> 00:00:45.954 align:middle line:84%
for months about
global currency resets

00:00:45.954 --> 00:00:49.950 align:middle line:84%
with people putting their lives
on hold waiting for windfalls.

00:00:49.950 --> 00:00:52.697 align:middle line:84%
Andy is here to help us
sort through the whole mess

00:00:52.697 --> 00:00:53.581 align:middle line:90%
and it is a mess.

00:00:53.581 --> 00:00:54.622 align:middle line:90%
>> Andrew Hoffman: It is.

00:00:54.622 --> 00:00:55.389 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Indeed.

00:00:55.389 --> 00:00:57.293 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's see, I have
a couple-- I have

00:00:57.293 --> 00:00:58.459 align:middle line:90%
some questions written down.

00:00:58.459 --> 00:01:01.195 align:middle line:84%
We can go where we want with it,
but we have to start somewhere.

00:01:01.195 --> 00:01:03.663 align:middle line:84%
First of all, let's talk
about the government shutdown.

00:01:03.663 --> 00:01:05.232 align:middle line:90%
What happened?

00:01:05.232 --> 00:01:07.201 align:middle line:90%
What's still happening?

00:01:07.201 --> 00:01:09.970 align:middle line:84%
What's likely to
be happening again?

00:01:09.970 --> 00:01:12.540 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: OK, well obviously
what's going on is just a lot

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:14.008 align:middle line:90%
of political posturing.

00:01:14.008 --> 00:01:17.144 align:middle line:84%
We did have a government
shutdown per se,

00:01:17.144 --> 00:01:20.881 align:middle line:90%
because they didn't fund it.

00:01:20.881 --> 00:01:23.570 align:middle line:84%
They need it to pay the bills
so they have to create a new

00:01:23.570 --> 00:01:26.153 align:middle line:84%
budget which they still haven't
done,so they've kicked the can

00:01:26.153 --> 00:01:29.389 align:middle line:84%
down the road into January
which we'll talk about again.

00:01:29.389 --> 00:01:31.789 align:middle line:84%
People believe that
the government actually

00:01:31.789 --> 00:01:34.825 align:middle line:84%
was shutdown when in fact
90 percent of the government

00:01:34.825 --> 00:01:36.995 align:middle line:84%
was still up and running,
that's why you still

00:01:36.995 --> 00:01:40.083 align:middle line:84%
got your mail and all these
other things which have now

00:01:40.083 --> 00:01:41.302 align:middle line:90%
been considered essential.

00:01:41.302 --> 00:01:44.480 align:middle line:84%
And on top of that, all the
people who were furlowed

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:47.035 align:middle line:84%
got unemployment
insurance, some of them

00:01:47.035 --> 00:01:49.410 align:middle line:84%
got unemployment insurance
and now they all got back pay.

00:01:49.410 --> 00:01:50.578 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Back pay,
I know I heard that.

00:01:50.578 --> 00:01:52.304 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: So, they got
basically a two and a half week

00:01:52.304 --> 00:01:52.478 align:middle line:90%
vacation.

00:01:52.478 --> 00:01:53.314 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Talking
about windfalls.

00:01:53.314 --> 00:01:54.381 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Yeah.

00:01:54.381 --> 00:01:56.941 align:middle line:84%
A two and a half week vacation
that we paid for and they got

00:01:56.941 --> 00:01:58.085 align:middle line:90%
paid overtime for it.

00:01:58.085 --> 00:02:00.454 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: And, yeah, where
did this money appear from?

00:02:00.454 --> 00:02:04.358 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Well, they made a
deal at the last second just

00:02:04.358 --> 00:02:07.795 align:middle line:84%
like the fiscal cliff deal last
year to kick the can again.

00:02:07.795 --> 00:02:10.197 align:middle line:84%
They didn't really
budget anything.

00:02:10.197 --> 00:02:12.633 align:middle line:84%
They said, "OK,
by December 13th,

00:02:12.633 --> 00:02:15.362 align:middle line:84%
we will have a long
term spending plan."

00:02:15.362 --> 00:02:16.570 align:middle line:90%
They didn't call it a budget.

00:02:16.570 --> 00:02:19.039 align:middle line:84%
Remember, we haven't had
a budget for five years.

00:02:19.039 --> 00:02:21.793 align:middle line:84%
December 13th is now only
four, five weeks away,

00:02:21.793 --> 00:02:23.676 align:middle line:90%
haven't heard a peep about it.

00:02:23.676 --> 00:02:25.092 align:middle line:84%
And if they don't
have that, we're

00:02:25.092 --> 00:02:26.926 align:middle line:84%
going to go through
the same process

00:02:26.926 --> 00:02:28.849 align:middle line:84%
early next year
because this deal

00:02:28.849 --> 00:02:32.120 align:middle line:84%
that they made only funded
the government through January

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:32.620 align:middle line:90%
15th.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:36.423 align:middle line:84%
So, it looks like just like
the fiscal cliff deal last year

00:02:36.423 --> 00:02:38.631 align:middle line:84%
and this deal a few
weeks ago, we're

00:02:38.631 --> 00:02:40.961 align:middle line:84%
going to go through
the same thing again.

00:02:40.961 --> 00:02:43.533 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: So, if you're
saying that what percentage

00:02:43.533 --> 00:02:46.033 align:middle line:84%
of the government of services
were actually still available?

00:02:46.033 --> 00:02:48.135 align:middle line:84%
I mean that-- >> Hoffman:
Just about everything.

00:02:48.135 --> 00:02:50.404 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the only things
that really close were parks.

00:02:50.404 --> 00:02:53.518 align:middle line:84%
They made a big deal
closing the memorial parks

00:02:53.518 --> 00:02:57.044 align:middle line:84%
as if you need to close a
memorial park-- >> Regina:

00:02:57.044 --> 00:02:57.544 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:02:57.544 --> 00:02:58.612 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- and
anger the veterans.

00:02:58.612 --> 00:03:01.081 align:middle line:84%
They had a million veteran
march to protest it.

00:03:01.081 --> 00:03:03.361 align:middle line:84%
They closed NASA,
you know, things

00:03:03.361 --> 00:03:04.918 align:middle line:90%
that really don't matter much.

00:03:04.918 --> 00:03:06.553 align:middle line:84%
But again, everyone
got paid anyway,

00:03:06.553 --> 00:03:07.955 align:middle line:90%
so it wasn't a real shutdown.

00:03:07.955 --> 00:03:10.679 align:middle line:84%
And the bigger issue
that was going on here

00:03:10.679 --> 00:03:12.388 align:middle line:84%
was this debt ceiling--
>> Regina: Right.

00:03:12.388 --> 00:03:14.262 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- which
all was part and parcel.

00:03:14.262 --> 00:03:16.463 align:middle line:84%
Remember the fiscal
year ends September 30th

00:03:16.463 --> 00:03:17.364 align:middle line:90%
for the government.

00:03:17.364 --> 00:03:18.632 align:middle line:84%
So, that's what
this was all about,

00:03:18.632 --> 00:03:20.340 align:middle line:84%
the fiscal year they
didn't have a budget

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:21.702 align:middle line:90%
because they never have one.

00:03:21.702 --> 00:03:23.854 align:middle line:84%
And also, because of
the deal that they

00:03:23.854 --> 00:03:27.141 align:middle line:84%
made earlier this year to kick
the can with the debt ceiling,

00:03:27.141 --> 00:03:29.443 align:middle line:90%
they pushed it to the same time.

00:03:29.443 --> 00:03:32.246 align:middle line:84%
What they agreed was to
move the debt ceiling again

00:03:32.246 --> 00:03:35.616 align:middle line:84%
to "delay it"
until February 7th.

00:03:35.616 --> 00:03:39.469 align:middle line:84%
So, again we're just growing
debt at a-- unfettered pace

00:03:39.469 --> 00:03:40.320 align:middle line:90%
right now.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:43.490 align:middle line:84%
But what people don't realize
about what this deal was,

00:03:43.490 --> 00:03:45.759 align:middle line:84%
remember you had the
Republicans like Boehner,

00:03:45.759 --> 00:03:46.727 align:middle line:90%
that's what I call him.

00:03:46.727 --> 00:03:49.224 align:middle line:84%
[Laughter ] >>
Regina: I like that.

00:03:49.224 --> 00:03:51.265 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: You know,
acting so tough about debt.

00:03:51.265 --> 00:03:52.663 align:middle line:84%
What they inserted
into this deal

00:03:52.663 --> 00:03:57.261 align:middle line:84%
is that any future legislation
that attempts to cap the debt

00:03:57.261 --> 00:04:00.562 align:middle line:84%
can be vetoed by the
President, but better yet

00:04:00.562 --> 00:04:04.007 align:middle line:84%
to override that veto, you
now need a two thirds majority

00:04:04.007 --> 00:04:06.914 align:middle line:84%
in both the House and the
Senate which will never happen.

00:04:06.914 --> 00:04:09.940 align:middle line:84%
So, essentially, we've gotten
rid of the debt ceiling

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:12.086 align:middle line:84%
permanently and that
will be very clear

00:04:12.086 --> 00:04:14.139 align:middle line:84%
when this whole
process goes through

00:04:14.139 --> 00:04:16.256 align:middle line:90%
in the next month or two.

00:04:16.256 --> 00:04:18.292 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: I read somewhere
a couple weeks ago.

00:04:18.292 --> 00:04:19.756 align:middle line:84%
It was talking about
the rate that which

00:04:19.756 --> 00:04:21.547 align:middle line:84%
we're racking up debt
and it was something,

00:04:21.547 --> 00:04:23.263 align:middle line:84%
correct me if I'm
wrong, something

00:04:23.263 --> 00:04:26.467 align:middle line:84%
appalling like 56,000
dollars a second

00:04:26.467 --> 00:04:28.188 align:middle line:84%
or a minute,
something like that.

00:04:28.188 --> 00:04:30.771 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Well, I haven't done
the math in terms of seconds.

00:04:30.771 --> 00:04:31.438 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:04:31.438 --> 00:04:33.937 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: But just last year
alone, it's about a trillion.

00:04:33.937 --> 00:04:34.942 align:middle line:90%
This year I should say.

00:04:34.942 --> 00:04:35.609 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:04:35.609 --> 00:04:37.942 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: And you remember
when Obama came into office

00:04:37.942 --> 00:04:40.581 align:middle line:84%
and this is not about him,
because as a Ponzi scheme,

00:04:40.581 --> 00:04:42.082 align:middle line:90%
it must grow exponentially.

00:04:42.082 --> 00:04:44.702 align:middle line:84%
This started back when
we got up the debt --

00:04:44.702 --> 00:04:46.019 align:middle line:90%
the gold standard in 1971.

00:04:46.019 --> 00:04:51.024 align:middle line:84%
But when Obama came into office,
admittedly during this crisis,

00:04:51.024 --> 00:04:53.327 align:middle line:84%
it was 10 trillion
was the national debt.

00:04:53.327 --> 00:04:55.162 align:middle line:90%
Now, it's over 17 trillion.

00:04:55.162 --> 00:04:58.132 align:middle line:84%
So, we've added over 7
trillion in just five years.

00:04:58.132 --> 00:05:01.086 align:middle line:84%
But not only that,
we also nationalized

00:05:01.086 --> 00:05:03.122 align:middle line:84%
Fannie Mae and Freddie
Mac-- >> Regina: Right.

00:05:03.122 --> 00:05:04.705 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- in
the last five years.

00:05:04.705 --> 00:05:06.705 align:middle line:84%
They have 5 trillion
dollars of debt themselves,

00:05:06.705 --> 00:05:08.469 align:middle line:84%
but that is now held
"off balance sheet."

00:05:08.469 --> 00:05:10.844 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: So, that's not part
of the total debt package?

00:05:10.844 --> 00:05:11.712 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Yeah,
but it's there.

00:05:11.712 --> 00:05:12.813 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:05:12.813 --> 00:05:14.300 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: And that means we've
added 12 trillion in the last

00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:14.800 align:middle line:90%
five years.

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:18.064 align:middle line:84%
And then you have what's called
unfunded liabilities which

00:05:18.064 --> 00:05:21.281 align:middle line:84%
means things like the promises
to pensioners, to Medicare,

00:05:21.281 --> 00:05:24.996 align:middle line:84%
to Social Security and the
estimates of those which

00:05:24.996 --> 00:05:27.839 align:middle line:84%
are rising exponentially
are anywhere from--

00:05:27.839 --> 00:05:29.630 align:middle line:84%
I've heard 50 trillion,
a hundred trillion.

00:05:29.630 --> 00:05:32.065 align:middle line:84%
I've even seen a
guy named Kotlikoff,

00:05:32.065 --> 00:05:35.702 align:middle line:84%
he said it's 220 trillion
and rising rapidly.

00:05:35.702 --> 00:05:38.172 align:middle line:84%
So, I mean we've been
broke for a very long time,

00:05:38.172 --> 00:05:40.104 align:middle line:84%
but now we're more
broke than ever.

00:05:40.104 --> 00:05:41.729 align:middle line:84%
And now that we're
actually getting rid

00:05:41.729 --> 00:05:44.275 align:middle line:84%
of the debt ceiling which
is kind of fait accompli,

00:05:44.275 --> 00:05:45.913 align:middle line:90%
it was going to happen anyway.

00:05:45.913 --> 00:05:46.914 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Right.

00:05:46.914 --> 00:05:48.713 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: I mean there's a
good chance that that number

00:05:48.713 --> 00:05:49.783 align:middle line:90%
can really go parabolic.

00:05:49.783 --> 00:05:52.953 align:middle line:84%
Remember we have all time
low interest rates right now.

00:05:52.953 --> 00:05:55.144 align:middle line:84%
And as interest
rates creep up just

00:05:55.144 --> 00:05:58.658 align:middle line:84%
by one percent when you
have-- let's say 12 trillion--

00:05:58.658 --> 00:06:02.029 align:middle line:84%
I'm sorry, 20 trillion
debt that adds 200 billion

00:06:02.029 --> 00:06:03.864 align:middle line:84%
of interest payments
for each 1 percent

00:06:03.864 --> 00:06:06.166 align:middle line:90%
that interest rates go up.

00:06:06.166 --> 00:06:08.677 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: OK, so we're now
within a range of unfathomable

00:06:08.677 --> 00:06:12.525 align:middle line:84%
numbers, you know, we don't
even or we can't get our minds

00:06:12.525 --> 00:06:13.407 align:middle line:90%
around it in general.

00:06:13.407 --> 00:06:14.908 align:middle line:90%
We don't understand.

00:06:14.908 --> 00:06:19.079 align:middle line:84%
I think how it could have been
allowed for us to get here

00:06:19.079 --> 00:06:21.731 align:middle line:84%
to begin with and no one
can really see a way out

00:06:21.731 --> 00:06:22.682 align:middle line:90%
of this point.

00:06:22.682 --> 00:06:25.743 align:middle line:84%
And so, just to put things in
perspective with the numbers

00:06:25.743 --> 00:06:26.887 align:middle line:90%
you just put up.

00:06:26.887 --> 00:06:29.479 align:middle line:84%
What is the gross domestic
product of the U.S.

00:06:29.479 --> 00:06:30.057 align:middle line:90%
for example?

00:06:30.057 --> 00:06:32.326 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Well, there's a lot
of different numbers out there.

00:06:32.326 --> 00:06:33.527 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah, yeah, I know.

00:06:33.527 --> 00:06:34.583 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's say
something that might

00:06:34.583 --> 00:06:35.929 align:middle line:90%
look like a genuine number.

00:06:35.929 --> 00:06:37.164 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Yeah.

00:06:37.164 --> 00:06:40.567 align:middle line:84%
Well, for the longest time,
it was around 15 trillion.

00:06:40.567 --> 00:06:43.537 align:middle line:84%
So, we're-- you know, that would
make us a 110 percent of GDP

00:06:43.537 --> 00:06:47.507 align:middle line:84%
or maybe a 130 percent if
you include the Fannie Mae,

00:06:47.507 --> 00:06:50.410 align:middle line:84%
Freddie Mac debt or whatever
number you want to pick.

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:53.672 align:middle line:84%
This summer-- this last
summer, the government secretly

00:06:53.672 --> 00:06:56.443 align:middle line:84%
changed their
calculation of GDP and I

00:06:56.443 --> 00:07:00.741 align:middle line:84%
think they added-- I don't know
20 or 30 percent to the number

00:07:00.741 --> 00:07:04.083 align:middle line:84%
by including intangibles
like goodwill and research

00:07:04.083 --> 00:07:06.663 align:middle line:84%
and lost money, and
research ventures

00:07:06.663 --> 00:07:10.002 align:middle line:84%
just because they want to
publish that the debt to GDP

00:07:10.002 --> 00:07:11.365 align:middle line:90%
number is lower.

00:07:11.365 --> 00:07:14.377 align:middle line:84%
But the fact is that doesn't
mask the fact that the debt is

00:07:14.377 --> 00:07:15.335 align:middle line:90%
still there and rising.

00:07:15.335 --> 00:07:16.895 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: From
your calculations,

00:07:16.895 --> 00:07:20.774 align:middle line:84%
do you think that that's 15
trillion is fair estimate?

00:07:20.774 --> 00:07:21.909 align:middle line:90%
Is that a realistic number?

00:07:21.909 --> 00:07:24.450 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: It's more realistic
than what they're putting out

00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:24.912 align:middle line:90%
there now.

00:07:24.912 --> 00:07:26.013 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: What
they're putting-- Yeah.

00:07:26.013 --> 00:07:27.948 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: But again, you know,
the rule of thumb with anything

00:07:27.948 --> 00:07:30.684 align:middle line:84%
the government puts out
regarding, well, anything.

00:07:30.684 --> 00:07:34.868 align:middle line:84%
But particularly economic data
is that it's pure lies and most

00:07:34.868 --> 00:07:37.024 align:middle line:84%
people don't follow
it like I do,

00:07:37.024 --> 00:07:41.140 align:middle line:84%
but everyone can see what's
going on with the unemployment

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:45.666 align:middle line:84%
rate which is been particularly
galling 'cause it started right

00:07:45.666 --> 00:07:49.256 align:middle line:84%
before last-- the last election
cycle and all of the sudden

00:07:49.256 --> 00:07:51.715 align:middle line:84%
the unemployment rates started
plunging-- >> Regina: Yeah--

00:07:51.715 --> 00:07:53.964 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- because of
the labor participation rate

00:07:53.964 --> 00:07:54.841 align:middle line:90%
plunging even faster.

00:07:54.841 --> 00:07:56.176 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: We're going to
get into that in just a sec.

00:07:56.176 --> 00:07:58.912 align:middle line:84%
I just have another question on
this whole Ponzi scheme thing.

00:07:58.912 --> 00:08:00.013 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Yes.

00:08:00.013 --> 00:08:02.888 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Can you give us a
historical example of a Ponzi

00:08:02.888 --> 00:08:06.320 align:middle line:84%
scheme that actually lasted a
really long time and worked?

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:08.322 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: No, because
that's the definition.

00:08:08.322 --> 00:08:10.613 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Because usually
they go bust-- - >> Hoffman:

00:08:10.613 --> 00:08:13.424 align:middle line:84%
The definition of Ponzi scheme
is any kind of marketing scheme

00:08:13.424 --> 00:08:17.326 align:middle line:84%
or any kind of financial scheme
in which it must grow larger

00:08:17.326 --> 00:08:18.098 align:middle line:90%
to survive.

00:08:18.098 --> 00:08:20.767 align:middle line:84%
And as it grows larger it
must do so exponentially,

00:08:20.767 --> 00:08:23.036 align:middle line:84%
that's why it's a
pyramid-- >> Regina: Right.

00:08:23.036 --> 00:08:27.607 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- that gets larger,
balancing on little point.

00:08:27.607 --> 00:08:29.076 align:middle line:90%
So, no, it's impossible.

00:08:29.076 --> 00:08:32.111 align:middle line:84%
It cannot, because any pyramid
scheme eventually collapses

00:08:32.111 --> 00:08:35.514 align:middle line:84%
either due to the size or
a sudden loss in confidence

00:08:35.514 --> 00:08:37.824 align:middle line:84%
and when it comes
to fiat currencies,

00:08:37.824 --> 00:08:41.842 align:middle line:84%
fiat meaning on back, there
have been 599 in the history

00:08:41.842 --> 00:08:43.991 align:middle line:84%
