printing.

00:09:33.407 --> 00:09:36.076 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Let's talk about--
let us go back to unemployment,

00:09:36.076 --> 00:09:38.612 align:middle line:84%
some of the unemployment
numbers, the real numbers.

00:09:38.612 --> 00:09:39.780 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Right.

00:09:39.780 --> 00:09:42.027 align:middle line:84%
Well, I was mentioning
the labor participation

00:09:42.027 --> 00:09:44.684 align:middle line:84%
rate, which generally means--
>> Regina: What does that mean?

00:09:44.684 --> 00:09:46.887 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: In generally
means the amount of people

00:09:46.887 --> 00:09:50.824 align:middle line:84%
in the potential labor force
that are actually working.

00:09:50.824 --> 00:09:53.026 align:middle line:84%
So, what happens with
the government is

00:09:53.026 --> 00:09:56.997 align:middle line:84%
if you are unemployed for--
well it used to be 52 weeks,

00:09:56.997 --> 00:10:00.200 align:middle line:84%
now they've got up to 99 weeks
the unemployment benefits.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:01.134 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: 99?

00:10:01.134 --> 00:10:03.509 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: In some places 99
weeks which means why work,

00:10:03.509 --> 00:10:04.008 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:10:04.008 --> 00:10:04.704 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:10:04.704 --> 00:10:06.106 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Or why try to work.

00:10:06.106 --> 00:10:09.443 align:middle line:84%
When you get out-- when
you no longer get benefits,

00:10:09.443 --> 00:10:11.778 align:middle line:84%
the government will no
longer consider you a person.

00:10:11.778 --> 00:10:15.382 align:middle line:84%
You're not in the denominator
of the unemployment rate.

00:10:15.382 --> 00:10:17.461 align:middle line:84%
So, as people--
less and less people

00:10:17.461 --> 00:10:20.672 align:middle line:84%
can get a job, less--
more and more people

00:10:20.672 --> 00:10:24.500 align:middle line:84%
fall off of that denominator
and therefore, the unemployment

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:26.526 align:middle line:90%
rate looks like it's falling.

00:10:26.526 --> 00:10:29.329 align:middle line:84%
But labor participation which
shows the percentage of people

00:10:29.329 --> 00:10:31.131 align:middle line:84%
that can work,
that actually are,

00:10:31.131 --> 00:10:32.732 align:middle line:84%
has been plummeting
at a record rate.

00:10:32.732 --> 00:10:35.402 align:middle line:90%
In fact, we hit a 35 year low.

00:10:35.402 --> 00:10:38.405 align:middle line:84%
I would say we hit that
low about a year ago

00:10:38.405 --> 00:10:40.574 align:middle line:84%
and each month
it's gotten worse.

00:10:40.574 --> 00:10:43.414 align:middle line:84%
Last month was the lowest
it's been since I think,

00:10:43.414 --> 00:10:46.947 align:middle line:84%
was it 1980 or something
like that or 1978?

00:10:46.947 --> 00:10:48.742 align:middle line:84%
So, the true state
of the economy

00:10:48.742 --> 00:10:50.117 align:middle line:84%
is unemployment
is getting worse,

00:10:50.117 --> 00:10:51.852 align:middle line:90%
but that's only part of it.

00:10:51.852 --> 00:10:56.490 align:middle line:84%
The type of jobs, the quality
of the jobs is plunging,

00:10:56.490 --> 00:11:00.828 align:middle line:84%
is weakening because we've
lost all of our manufacturing

00:11:00.828 --> 00:11:01.328 align:middle line:90%
capability.

00:11:01.328 --> 00:11:03.799 align:middle line:84%
We sold it out to the east,
and part of-- >> Regina: Right.

00:11:03.799 --> 00:11:05.632 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: It would
have gone there anyway,

00:11:05.632 --> 00:11:08.690 align:middle line:84%
because they have low cost, but
also because of all the trade

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:13.573 align:middle line:84%
deals that were lobbied for in
the 1980s like GATT and NAFTA--

00:11:13.573 --> 00:11:14.674 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Right.

00:11:14.674 --> 00:11:16.548 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- have
accelerated that process.

00:11:16.548 --> 00:11:19.053 align:middle line:84%
So, the jobs that we have now
which aren't even keeping up

00:11:19.053 --> 00:11:21.699 align:middle line:84%
with the growth
of the population:

00:11:21.699 --> 00:11:24.814 align:middle line:84%
waiters, bartenders, a lot
of part time jobs and we're

00:11:24.814 --> 00:11:26.584 align:middle line:84%
going to talk about
Obamacare and what

00:11:26.584 --> 00:11:28.522 align:middle line:84%
that's going to do--
>> Regina: Yup, we are.

00:11:28.522 --> 00:11:29.289 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- with
the part time jobs.

00:11:29.289 --> 00:11:30.323 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:11:30.323 --> 00:11:33.450 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: So, what is the true
percentage of unemployment look

00:11:33.450 --> 00:11:34.194 align:middle line:90%
like?

00:11:34.194 --> 00:11:37.597 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: There's a guy named
John Williams and not the Star

00:11:37.597 --> 00:11:38.431 align:middle line:90%
Wars composer.

00:11:38.431 --> 00:11:39.533 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:11:39.533 --> 00:11:41.491 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: He has a
website called ShadowStats

00:11:41.491 --> 00:11:43.336 align:middle line:90%
and he's been doing alternative.

00:11:43.336 --> 00:11:47.407 align:middle line:84%
He's the premier alternative
economic information guy.

00:11:47.407 --> 00:11:49.549 align:middle line:84%
So, he's got the
real inflation rate

00:11:49.549 --> 00:11:53.113 align:middle line:84%
which has been hovering around
8 or 10 percent for years.

00:11:53.113 --> 00:11:54.833 align:middle line:84%
And when it comes
to unemployment

00:11:54.833 --> 00:11:56.208 align:middle line:84%
there's three
different measures.

00:11:56.208 --> 00:11:58.576 align:middle line:84%
The government gives their
bogus 7 percent or whatever

00:11:58.576 --> 00:12:00.053 align:middle line:90%
it is, 7 and a half.

00:12:00.053 --> 00:12:01.815 align:middle line:84%
And, you know, the
real rate-- if you

00:12:01.815 --> 00:12:03.960 align:middle line:84%
talk about people
who are-- as I put it

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:06.660 align:middle line:84%
who can't pay the bills because
either they're not working

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:09.456 align:middle line:84%
or they're working part time,
or they're not making enough

00:12:09.456 --> 00:12:10.497 align:middle line:90%
'cause it's minimum wage.

00:12:10.497 --> 00:12:13.002 align:middle line:84%
It's, you know, close to 25
percent-- >> Regina: Right.

00:12:13.002 --> 00:12:15.335 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- which is not
far from the depression era.

00:12:15.335 --> 00:12:16.303 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: 25 percent.

00:12:16.303 --> 00:12:17.011 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Yeah.

00:12:17.011 --> 00:12:17.838 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yeah.

00:12:17.838 --> 00:12:19.673 align:middle line:84%
That's the number I've heard
bandied about about as well.

00:12:19.673 --> 00:12:20.440 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: The underemployment.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:21.474 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Underemployment rate.

00:12:21.474 --> 00:12:22.183 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Yeah.

00:12:22.183 --> 00:12:23.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Yeah, which
is as significant.

00:12:23.890 --> 00:12:25.779 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's the true
state of the economy.

00:12:25.779 --> 00:12:26.889 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Yes.

00:12:26.889 --> 00:12:28.805 align:middle line:84%
And when you've had a
fed that's been printing

00:12:28.805 --> 00:12:30.350 align:middle line:84%
unfettered money
for 40 years or,

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:33.553 align:middle line:84%
you can go back-- it
started a hundred years ago.

00:12:33.553 --> 00:12:36.521 align:middle line:84%
Inflation has been so
bad that that trend only

00:12:36.521 --> 00:12:38.558 align:middle line:84%
makes the standard of
living that much worse

00:12:38.558 --> 00:12:41.728 align:middle line:84%
which is why we have all
time highs in food stamps

00:12:41.728 --> 00:12:44.431 align:middle line:84%
and disability and
entitlements of all kinds.

00:12:44.431 --> 00:12:45.732 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yes.

00:12:45.732 --> 00:12:48.320 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's talk about federal
reserve tapering or taperings,

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:49.236 align:middle line:90%
a subject of tapering.

00:12:49.236 --> 00:12:50.470 align:middle line:90%
What does that mean?

00:12:50.470 --> 00:12:51.438 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Right.

00:12:51.438 --> 00:12:54.307 align:middle line:84%
Well, the-- I'm sure everyone
listening has heard the term

00:12:54.307 --> 00:12:55.140 align:middle line:90%
quantitative easing.

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:55.766 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Yes.

00:12:55.766 --> 00:12:58.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: It's just a fed
euphemism for printing money.

00:12:58.140 --> 00:12:58.945 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Right.

00:12:58.945 --> 00:13:00.819 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Now, the
fed, generally speaking,

00:13:00.819 --> 00:13:04.529 align:middle line:84%
does kind of behind the scenes
printing money when it keeps

00:13:04.529 --> 00:13:07.492 align:middle line:84%
its fed funds rate at zero which
is where it's been for five

00:13:07.492 --> 00:13:09.656 align:middle line:84%
years, where they're--
on daily basis,

00:13:09.656 --> 00:13:13.293 align:middle line:84%
they're buying short term
bonds to keep rates down.

00:13:13.293 --> 00:13:15.009 align:middle line:84%
But quantitative
easing literally

00:13:15.009 --> 00:13:18.846 align:middle line:84%
means printing money and
monetizing well any kind

00:13:18.846 --> 00:13:19.866 align:middle line:90%
of securities.

00:13:19.866 --> 00:13:23.135 align:middle line:84%
Right now, they're monetizing
treasury bonds and mortgage

00:13:23.135 --> 00:13:25.827 align:middle line:84%
backed securities, probably
behind the scenes they're

00:13:25.827 --> 00:13:27.355 align:middle line:84%
monetizing stocks
because they have

00:13:27.355 --> 00:13:30.043 align:middle line:84%
- the President's working
group in financial markets.

00:13:30.043 --> 00:13:31.211 align:middle line:90%
It's their job to do that.

00:13:31.211 --> 00:13:32.078 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Right.

00:13:32.078 --> 00:13:33.536 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: But
generally speaking,

00:13:33.536 --> 00:13:37.666 align:middle line:84%
since 2008 they've been on
an overt quantitative easing

00:13:37.666 --> 00:13:40.706 align:middle line:84%
program where they buy these
things every month to keep

00:13:40.706 --> 00:13:41.254 align:middle line:90%
rates down.

00:13:41.254 --> 00:13:45.123 align:middle line:84%
And unbelievably, they now own a
third of all the treasury bonds

00:13:45.123 --> 00:13:48.428 align:middle line:84%
outstanding and a half of all
the mortgage bonds outstanding,

00:13:48.428 --> 00:13:50.393 align:middle line:84%
plus they owned
Fannie Mae, so they

00:13:50.393 --> 00:13:52.518 align:middle line:84%
originate and own pretty
much every mortgage that's

00:13:52.518 --> 00:13:52.966 align:middle line:90%
out there.

00:13:52.966 --> 00:13:54.501 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: And you say they're
also in the stock market

00:13:54.501 --> 00:13:55.914 align:middle line:90%
as well now, you think.

00:13:55.914 --> 00:13:58.038 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Oh, I know
they're in the stock market.

00:13:58.038 --> 00:13:59.906 align:middle line:90%
But they don't tell you that.

00:13:59.906 --> 00:14:02.676 align:middle line:84%
That's not something that
they give numbers for.

00:14:02.676 --> 00:14:04.559 align:middle line:84%
But for quantitative
easing, the fed

00:14:04.559 --> 00:14:07.480 align:middle line:84%
says we are buying now 85
billion dollars a month,

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:10.150 align:middle line:84%
we are printing and buying
85 billion dollars a month

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:11.697 align:middle line:84%
worth of treasuries
and mortgages

00:14:11.697 --> 00:14:14.464 align:middle line:84%
and just last week, they
reiterated that they're

00:14:14.464 --> 00:14:16.156 align:middle line:90%
doing it ad infinitum.

00:14:16.156 --> 00:14:18.378 align:middle line:84%
And at some point, they're
going to own all of them

00:14:18.378 --> 00:14:20.204 align:middle line:84%
and they have to
keep increasing it

00:14:20.204 --> 00:14:22.853 align:middle line:84%
because the only other
major owners in the world

00:14:22.853 --> 00:14:24.230 align:middle line:90%
are the Chinese and Japanese.

00:14:24.230 --> 00:14:26.774 align:middle line:84%
The Japanese have stopped
buying and the Chinese

00:14:26.774 --> 00:14:28.034 align:middle line:90%
are now actively selling.

00:14:28.034 --> 00:14:30.136 align:middle line:84%
So, when they talk
about tapering,

00:14:30.136 --> 00:14:31.671 align:middle line:90%
tapering is just a ruse.

00:14:31.671 --> 00:14:34.374 align:middle line:84%
It's been for the last five
years, in fact my piece

00:14:34.374 --> 00:14:37.410 align:middle line:84%
that I wrote today is about the
history of all these things.

00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:40.146 align:middle line:84%
At one point they called
it the exit strategy.

00:14:40.146 --> 00:14:42.816 align:middle line:84%
They said, we saw green
shoots of recovery

00:14:42.816 --> 00:14:46.753 align:middle line:84%
and this year it became tapering
which would mean slowing down,

00:14:46.753 --> 00:14:50.455 align:middle line:84%
not stopping, slowing down
the pace of printing money

00:14:50.455 --> 00:14:53.760 align:middle line:84%
and monetizing bonds But the
fact is they never do it,

00:14:53.760 --> 00:14:56.781 align:middle line:84%
because the economy keeps
getting worse and anytime they

00:14:56.781 --> 00:14:58.231 align:middle line:90%
even talk about it.

00:14:58.231 --> 00:14:59.743 align:middle line:84%
They started this
year in February

00:14:59.743 --> 00:15:01.070 align:middle line:90%
talking about it again.

00:15:01.070 --> 00:15:02.994 align:middle line:84%
Interest rates jumped
up and immediately

00:15:02.994 --> 00:15:05.099 align:middle line:84%
the fed governors came
out and say, no, we're

00:15:05.099 --> 00:15:05.739 align:middle line:90%
not going to do this.

00:15:05.739 --> 00:15:07.006 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Nope, can't do that.

00:15:07.006 --> 00:15:08.641 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: And yet they still
said in September, I mean,

00:15:08.641 --> 00:15:10.099 align:middle line:84%
the media is saying
it's September.

00:15:10.099 --> 00:15:11.411 align:middle line:90%
Well, I think they might do it.

00:15:11.411 --> 00:15:13.313 align:middle line:84%
I was out there saying there's
not a chance they'll do it.

00:15:13.313 --> 00:15:14.047 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: No way.

00:15:14.047 --> 00:15:15.148 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: And they didn't.

00:15:15.148 --> 00:15:16.355 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: Grind to a hault
the housing market and other

00:15:16.355 --> 00:15:17.146 align:middle line:90%
aspects of economy.

00:15:17.146 --> 00:15:17.855 align:middle line:90%
They can't do it.

00:15:17.855 --> 00:15:20.312 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: The housing market
has rolled over dramatically

00:15:20.312 --> 00:15:22.615 align:middle line:84%
just since that dumb comment
that-- >> Regina: Yeah.

00:15:22.615 --> 00:15:23.823 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: -- Bernanke made.

00:15:23.823 --> 00:15:25.948 align:middle line:84%
And all he said was, and
this was in June, he said,

00:15:25.948 --> 00:15:29.929 align:middle line:84%
"If the economy improves,
we might taper."

00:15:29.929 --> 00:15:31.698 align:middle line:90%
And the economy got worse.

00:15:31.698 --> 00:15:32.407 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Right.

00:15:32.407 --> 00:15:34.614 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: And now the
government shutdown only made

00:15:34.614 --> 00:15:35.168 align:middle line:90%
things worse.

00:15:35.168 --> 00:15:37.737 align:middle line:84%
And now, they have another
government shutdown coming up

00:15:37.737 --> 00:15:39.639 align:middle line:84%
and now the housing
market's rolling over.

00:15:39.639 --> 00:15:40.874 align:middle line:90%
>> Regina: Exactly.

00:15:40.874 --> 00:15:43.082 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: Any real economic
data you see out there,

00:15:43.082 --> 00:15:45.111 align:middle line:84%
not these diffusion
indices where it says well,

00:15:45.111 --> 00:15:47.680 align:middle line:84%
if it goes from 51 to
52, things are better.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:50.250 align:middle line:84%
Those are just surveys
that don't mean anything.

00:15:50.250 --> 00:15:53.234 align:middle line:84%
But if you look at
durable goods orders,

00:15:53.234 --> 00:15:55.505 align:middle line:84%
retail sales,
capital expenditures,

00:15:55.505 --> 00:15:58.610 align:middle line:84%
consumer confidence,
everything that's real

00:15:58.610 --> 00:16:00.727 align:middle line:90%
has been dramatically declining.

00:16:00.727 --> 00:16:03.696 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: What about the--
every time we talk I forget.

00:16:03.696 --> 00:16:06.666 align:middle line:84%
I should write it down
beforehand-- the Baltic Index--

00:16:06.666 --> 00:16:07.700 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Dry Index.

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:08.735 align:middle line:84%
>> Regina: -- Dry
Index, Baltic Dry Index.

00:16:08.735 --> 00:16:09.936 align:middle line:90%
>> Hoffman: Right.

00:16:09.936 --> 00:16:14.120 align:middle line:84%
The Baltic Dry Index
is a strange measure

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:17.410 align:middle line:84%
of shipping because it
combines global shipping.

00:16:17.410 --> 00:16:19.145 align:middle line:90%
It combines-- >> Regina: Right.

00:16:19.145 --> 00:16:21.502 align:middle line:84%
>> Hoffman: -- the prices
of the-- the activity

00:16:21.502 --> 00:16:24.150 align:middle line:84%
of the tankers and the
prices of the tankers.

00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:26.397 align:middle line:84%
It can be misleading
though because there

00:16:26.397 --> 00:16:30.156 align:middle line:84%
was a huge glut when times were
good, five years ago or so,

00:16:30.156 --> 00:16:31.277 align:middle line:90%
when the economy was good.

